# Introduction
## What is Apollo?
Have you ever heard of Zork and wondered "Man, I'd love to make my own oldschool text-based interactive novel, but it's toooo much work!"? Well, say no more!

Apollo is an easy to use interactive novel creator, easy and powerful at the same time!
## Introduction to Apollo Editor
Apollo Editor window consists of three parts:
![Apollo Editor window](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Tree with all dialogs and their options
2. Visual graph of your story, so you won't get lost
3. Dialog/Dialog option editor

## Story tree

![Apollo story tree](data:image/png;base64,)

Story tree is quite simple, every element has following structure:
- Dialog
  - Option
  - Option
  - Option

Flag indicates, that this dialog will start your story.

To add dialog, simply press first button, that one with a plus sign. It will add a new dialog at the end of the tree.

When you want to add dialog option, that's what the second button with a plus is for. If selected item is dialog option, it will add option to selected element's parent, else it will add it to selected dialog.

To remove dialog _or_ its option, simply press button with a minus.

Small buttons with arrows allow you to organize story tree a bit, although Apollo doesn't really care about elements' order (one exception - we will get to that later).

## Visual diagram
![Visual story diagram](data:image/png;base64,)

Visual diagram is a little help for you, so you won't get lost in your story diagram.

Items here are just dialogs, and lines connecting them - their options. On this diagram we can see, that this story consists of two dialogs and three options - as diagram goes by default from left to right, all three options are children of "Begin" dialog, and point to "Second" dialog.

You have noticed that *by default*, huh? Well, you can move those items around! And it gets even better, because this layout will be saved! Just, you know, don't consider .apmap files unnecessary.

Now, you see that arrows in bottom right corner? Click them, zoombox will open. Here you can fool around with zooming in and out.

## Dialog (option) editor
#### Dialog editor
![Dialog editor](data:image/png;base64,)
#### Dialog option editor
![Dialog option editor](data:image/png;base64,)
This is place when you can modify you dialogs. Here we have a few fields for you to play.

### General
These fields are the same for both dialog and dialog option.
#### Short name
It's just a name for you to distinguish this dialog (option). Apollo **doesn't** care about them. 

Well, maybe except one case. _**WARNING: Advanced stuff over here.**_

There is one special name for dialog option, and that is `:cont`. It makes Apollo ignore all other dialog options and even this dialog's content. It takes content from a field in story settings called *Continue string*, which is by default `Press any key to continue...`. It waits for any input and goes straight to the *Target*. It's the only moment when elements' order on Story Tree matters - Apollo takes first available `:cont` dialog option (that is, first one which *Requirement* is empty or evaluates to `True` - see [Requirements and Actions](Requirements_and_Actions) for more)
#### Content
Thats what this is all about. You have here a few toys to play too.
##### Text and Background
These set colors of, as you might have already guessed, text and its background. You have 16 options to choose from - see [Colors](Colors) for more.
##### Reset color
Not much to explain here. It just sets colors back to story's default ones. You can reset text, background or both.
##### Invert color
Just swaps text and background colors. Duh.
##### Expression
_**WARNING: Advanced stuff over here.**_
It allows you to insert an expression, which result will be inserted into text. See [Expressions](Expressions) for more.
##### Insert variable
It allows you to insert variable into text. See [Variables](Variables) for more.

### Dialogs only
#### Is start dialog
Selecting this will make current dialog the beginning one. It will also deselect old one, because only one dialog can start a story.
#### Actions
_**WARNING: Advanced stuff over here.**_
Here you can set actions to execute **before** content is written onto the screen. You can have multiple expressions here, just put them all in separate lines. See [Requirements and Actions](Requirements_and_Actions) for more.
#### ID
It shows dialog's ID, the same one you can find as *Target* in dialogs. Just FYI, you can't change it.

### Dialog options only
#### Requirement
_**WARNING: Advanced stuff over here.**_
Expression here must evaluate to `True` or `1` in order for option to be active. You have only one line of expressions here, but you can use *AND* and *OR*. I believe in you, you can do this. See [Requirements and Actions](Requirements_and_Actions) for more.
#### Target
When this option will be selected, *Target* will become the next shown dialog. To change it, simply double click on field and select a new one from Diagram.

If you ever see a dialog option when previewing a story like this:
```
[t] Option
```
it means that this option doesn't have any target.

## Story properties
You can access them through File menu on top of the window.
![Story properties](data:image/png;base64,)

### Title
Every good story needs a title!
### Author
Hey, it's you!
### Description
Tell people something about your story.
### Continue string
This will show when using `:cont` dialog options or when story ends
### Default text/background color
Well, I think this is descriptive. They just set default text and background colors for your story.
